<paragraph id="6409E01DFF95623AFF6F1050FDCEADEB" blockId="7.[164,778,1133,1186]" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">
<emphasis id="56C23C0FFF95623AFF6F1050FEFCADCA" box="[164,312,1134,1155]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">
<typeStatus id="BB0D5EBFFF95623AFF6F1050FF1CADCA" box="[164,216,1134,1155]" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">Type</typeStatus>
species:
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="A3B69B9EFF95623AFE8F1050FDB3ADCA" authority="Hogg, 1905" authorityName="Hogg" authorityYear="1905" box="[324,631,1133,1155]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Lycosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="errans">
<emphasis id="56C23C0FFF95623AFE8F1050FE21ADCA" box="[324,485,1134,1155]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">Lycosa errans</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="00279DECFF95623AFE3A1053FDB3ADCA" author="Hogg HR" box="[497,631,1133,1155]" pageId="7" pageNumber="90" pagination="569 - 590" refId="ref23290" refString="Hogg HR. 1905. On some South Australian spiders of the family Lycosidae. Proceedings of the Zoological Society London 1905: 569 - 590." type="journal article" year="1905">Hogg, 1905</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(by original designation). Gender feminine.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6409E01DFF95623AFF6F10E9FE5AAE78" blockId="7.[164,779,1238,1903]" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">
<emphasis id="56C23C0FFF95623AFF6F10E9FE5CADA5" box="[164,408,1239,1260]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">
Diagnosis: 
<taxonomicName id="A3B69B9EFF95623AFEEF10E9FE5CADA5" authorityName="Roewer" authorityYear="1955" box="[292,408,1239,1260]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Hoggicosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hoggicosa</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
differs from other 
<taxonomicName id="A3B69B9EFF95623AFDBC10E8FD23ADA5" authorityName="Sundevall" authorityYear="1833" box="[631,743,1238,1260]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Lycosinae">Lycosinae</taxonomicName>
by a combination of genitalic and somatic characters. A putative synapomorphy is proposed based on the female epigyne, with the distance between the anterior pockets greater than the width of the posterior transverse part (
<figureCitation id="FC8DFC98FF95623AFEAE1151FE7AACCD" box="[357,446,1391,1413]" captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="30.[144,223,1824,1843]" captionTargetBox="[403,1164,940,1790]" captionTargetId="figure-79@30.[399,1167,937,1794]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="Figure 8. Hoggicosa castanea (Hogg). A–B, palp, ♂ from Gluepot Station, South Australia (SA), SAM NN19314. A, ventral; B, palea. C–D, epigynum, ♀ from Fisherman Point, Lincoln National Park, SA, SAM NN15185. C, ventral; D, dorsal. Scale bars = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5447869" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5447869/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">Figs 8C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="FC8DFC98FF95623AFE001151FE3EACCC" box="[459,506,1391,1413]" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="32.[144,223,1225,1244]" captionTargetBox="[411,1153,199,1192]" captionTargetId="figure-0@32.[408,1157,195,1195]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="Figure 11. Hoggicosa alfi sp. nov. A–B, palp, ♂ paratype from Lorna Glen Station, Western Australia (WA), WAM T53919. A, ventral; B, palea. C–D, epigynum, ♀ paratype, from Lorna Glen Station, WA, WAM T77406. C, ventral; D, dorsal. E, epigynum, dorsal, ♀ variation from Nanga Station, WA, WAM T62772. Scale bars = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5447873" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5447873/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">11C</figureCitation>
). An undescribed genus from 
<collectingCountry id="1CA1A08DFF95623AFF2E11B0FEEFACED" box="[229,299,1422,1444]" name="Brazil" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">Brazil</collectingCountry>
shares this trait; however, the anterior pockets extend along the anterior margin of the epigyne and join in a groove, forming somewhat of an ‘m’ shape (see 
<bibRefCitation id="00279DECFF95623AFE8411D6FE35AF49" author="Alvares ESS" box="[335,497,1512,1536]" pageId="7" pageNumber="90" refId="ref22234" refString="Alvares ESS. 2006. A Subfamilia Lycosinae no Brasil (Araneae, Lycosidae), com notas sobre especies correntes em paises limitrofes. Unpublished Masters Thesis, Instituto de Biociencias da Universidade de Sao Paulo." type="book" year="2006">Álvares, 2006</bibRefCitation>
: figs 127–150). A second synapomorphy is a patch of ten to 30 dorsally curved macrosetae on the tip of the cymbium in males (
<figureCitation id="FC8DFC98FF95623AFF67127BFF33AF15" box="[172,247,1605,1628]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="25.[164,243,1675,1694]" captionTargetBox="[261,1346,195,1645]" captionTargetId="figure-0@25.[261,1346,195,1645]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="Figure 1. Hoggicosa species, habitus photos (A–H) and male diagnostic character (I). A, Hoggicosa bicolor (Hogg) penultimate ♂ from Western Australia (WA), not registered. B, H. bicolor (Hogg) adult ♂ from Lorna Glen Station, WA, WAM T70329. C, Hoggicosa forresti (McKay, 1973) adult male from Lorna Glen Station, WA, WAM T65610. D, Hoggicosa storri (McKay) penultimate ♂ from WA, not registered. E, H. storri (McKay) adult ♂ from Lorna Glen Station, WA, WAM T70277. F, Hoggicosa natashae sp. nov. holotype ♀ from Lake Gilles, SA, SAM NN14785, Photo courtesy of D. Hirst. G, Hoggicosa alfi sp. nov. ♂ from type locality, Lorna Glen Station, WA, not registered. H, H. alfi sp. nov. ♀ from type locality, WAM T70334. I, Hoggicosa castanea (Hogg) lateral view of male cymbium tip with diagnostic macrosetae bent dorsally, from Gluepot Station, SA, SAM NN19314. Scale bars = 5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5447855" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5447855/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">Fig. 1I</figureCitation>
). In lateral view, the shield of the prosoma is highest in the cephalic region sloping gently towards posterior end (
<figureCitation id="FC8DFC98FF95623AFE9E12BDFE6FAFD0" box="[341,427,1667,1689]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="26.[144,223,1882,1901]" captionTargetBox="[401,1166,1578,1851]" captionTargetId="figure-73@26.[399,1167,1576,1853]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="Figure 3. Hoggicosa castanea (Hogg) carapace. A, lateral view. B, frontal view. Scale bars = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5447859" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5447859/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">Fig. 3A</figureCitation>
). The prosoma is uniform in colour or with indistinct radial pattern; median or lateral bands are absent. Females of several species show striking contrast in the colouration of the legs and opisthosoma (similarly coloured as penultimate males, 
<figureCitation id="FC8DFC98FF95623AFF3C1322FE56AE78" box="[247,402,1820,1842]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="25.[164,243,1675,1694]" captionTargetBox="[261,1346,195,1645]" captionTargetId="figure-0@25.[261,1346,195,1645]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="Figure 1. Hoggicosa species, habitus photos (A–H) and male diagnostic character (I). A, Hoggicosa bicolor (Hogg) penultimate ♂ from Western Australia (WA), not registered. B, H. bicolor (Hogg) adult ♂ from Lorna Glen Station, WA, WAM T70329. C, Hoggicosa forresti (McKay, 1973) adult male from Lorna Glen Station, WA, WAM T65610. D, Hoggicosa storri (McKay) penultimate ♂ from WA, not registered. E, H. storri (McKay) adult ♂ from Lorna Glen Station, WA, WAM T70277. F, Hoggicosa natashae sp. nov. holotype ♀ from Lake Gilles, SA, SAM NN14785, Photo courtesy of D. Hirst. G, Hoggicosa alfi sp. nov. ♂ from type locality, Lorna Glen Station, WA, not registered. H, H. alfi sp. nov. ♀ from type locality, WAM T70334. I, Hoggicosa castanea (Hogg) lateral view of male cymbium tip with diagnostic macrosetae bent dorsally, from Gluepot Station, SA, SAM NN19314. Scale bars = 5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5447855" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5447855/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">Fig. 1A, D, F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6409E01DFF95623AFF771305FB53A8A6" blockId="7.[164,779,1238,1903]" lastBlockId="7.[826,1441,198,495]" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">
Most similar to 
<taxonomicName id="A3B69B9EFF95623AFEBF1305FE2CAE19" authorityName="Roewer" authorityYear="1955" box="[372,488,1851,1872]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Hoggicosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="56C23C0FFF95623AFEBF1305FE2CAE19" box="[372,488,1851,1872]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">Hoggicosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the monotypic genus 
<taxonomicName id="A3B69B9EFF95623AFF6F1367FF3CAE27" authorityName="Framenau" authorityYear="2006" box="[164,248,1881,1902]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Knoelle" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="56C23C0FFF95623AFF6F1367FF3CAE27" box="[164,248,1881,1902]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">Knoelle</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and an undescribed Australian genus represented by the ‘Grey Wolf Spider’ (see 
<bibRefCitation id="00279DECFF95623AFAE114F8FC22A9B2" author="Framenau VW &amp; Baehr BC" pageId="7" pageNumber="90" pagination="1603 - 1629" refId="ref22721" refString="Framenau VW, Baehr BC. 2007. Revision of the Australian wolf spider genus Dingosa Roewer, 1955 (Araneae, Lycosidae). Journal of Natural History 41: 1603 - 1629." type="journal article" year="2007">Framenau &amp; Baehr, 2007</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="A3B69B9EFF95623AFC3114DAFB8AA9B0" authorityName="Framenau" authorityYear="2006" box="[1018,1102,228,249]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Knoelle" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="56C23C0FFF95623AFC3114DAFB8AA9B0" box="[1018,1102,228,249]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">Knoelle</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also possess backwards bent macrosetae on the cymbium tip, but in a much larger patch than in 
<taxonomicName id="A3B69B9EFF95623AFC34151CFBB7A87E" authorityName="Roewer" authorityYear="1955" box="[1023,1139,290,311]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Hoggicosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="56C23C0FFF95623AFC34151CFBB7A87E" box="[1023,1139,290,311]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">Hoggicosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation id="00279DECFF95623AFB0E151CFA59A871" author="Framenau VW" box="[1221,1437,290,312]" pageId="7" pageNumber="90" pagination="55 - 67" refId="ref22648" refString="Framenau VW. 2006 b. Knoelle, a new monotypic wolf spider genus from Australia (Araneae: Lycosidae). Zootaxa 1281: 55 - 67." type="journal article" year="2006">Framenau, 2006b</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 2). Specimens of the currently undescribed genus including the ‘Grey Wolf Spider’ [
<bibRefCitation id="00279DECFF95623AFB291561FA59A83C" author="Hickman VV" box="[1250,1437,351,373]" pageId="7" pageNumber="90" refId="ref23237" refString="Hickman VV. 1967. Some common spiders of Tasmania. Hobart: Tasmanian Museum and Art Gallery." type="book" year="1967">Hickman, 1967</bibRefCitation>
: misidentified as 
<taxonomicName id="A3B69B9EFF95623AFC351540FAAFA8DD" authority="(Simon, 1898)" baseAuthorityName="Simon" baseAuthorityYear="1898" box="[1022,1387,381,404]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Dingosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simsoni">
<emphasis id="56C23C0FFF95623AFC351540FB79A8DA" box="[1022,1213,382,403]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">Dingosa simsoni</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="00279DECFF95623AFB1B1543FAA7A8DD" author="Simon E" box="[1232,1379,381,404]" pageId="7" pageNumber="90" pagination="5 - 34" refId="ref24221" refString="Simon E. 1898. Descriptions d'arachnides nouveaux des familles des Agelenidae, Pisauridae, Lycosidae et Oxyopidae. Annales de la Societe Entomologique de Belgique 42: 5 - 34." type="journal article" year="1898">Simon, 1898</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
] are of similar size and shape as 
<taxonomicName id="A3B69B9EFF95623AFB5115A3FAAEA8FB" box="[1178,1386,412,434]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Hoggicosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="56C23C0FFF95623AFB5115A3FACAA8FB" box="[1178,1294,413,434]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">Hoggicosa</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
and build burrows with trapdoors, but they differ by the synapomorphies of 
<taxonomicName id="A3B69B9EFF95623AFBD715E4FB54A8A6" authorityName="Roewer" authorityYear="1955" box="[1052,1168,474,495]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Hoggicosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="56C23C0FFF95623AFBD715E4FB54A8A6" box="[1052,1168,474,495]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">Hoggicosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6409E01DFF95623AFCF11608FC5DADE6" blockId="7.[826,1441,565,1199]" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">
<emphasis id="56C23C0FFF95623AFCF11608FC06AB02" box="[826,962,566,587]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">Description:</emphasis>
Large and robust wolf spiders, TL 
<quantity id="A34E4DF8FF95623AFAAE160BFC55AB23" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.2164" metricValueMax="5.4864" metricValueMin="2.9463999999999997" pageId="7" pageNumber="90" unit="in" value="16.6" valueMax="21.6" valueMin="11.6">11.6– 21.6 in</quantity>
males and 
<quantity id="A34E4DF8FF95623AFBE6166DFB05AB23" box="[1069,1217,595,618]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.08" metricValueMax="6.5024" metricValueMin="3.6576" pageId="7" pageNumber="90" unit="in" value="20.0" valueMax="25.6" valueMin="14.4">14.4–25.6 in</quantity>
females. Prosoma longer than wide, length 
<quantity id="A34E4DF8FF95623AFBAE164CFB21ABC1" box="[1125,1253,626,648]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2606" metricValueMax="2.8956" metricValueMin="1.6256" pageId="7" pageNumber="90" unit="in" value="8.9" valueMax="11.4" valueMin="6.4">6.4–11.4 in</quantity>
males and 
<quantity id="A34E4DF8FF95623AFABA164CFC4FABEE" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2352" metricValueMax="2.7177999999999995" metricValueMin="1.7526" pageId="7" pageNumber="90" unit="in" value="8.8" valueMax="10.7" valueMin="6.9">6.9– 10.7 in</quantity>
females. Dorsal shield of prosoma highest in cephalic region, sloping gently towards posterior end (
<figureCitation id="FC8DFC98FF95623AFC8916F0FC5CABAD" box="[834,920,718,740]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="26.[144,223,1882,1901]" captionTargetBox="[401,1166,1578,1851]" captionTargetId="figure-73@26.[399,1167,1576,1853]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="Figure 3. Hoggicosa castanea (Hogg) carapace. A, lateral view. B, frontal view. Scale bars = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5447859" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5447859/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">Fig. 3A</figureCitation>
). Dorsal shield of prosoma uniform in colour or with faint radial pattern (sometimes artificially pronounced when preserved in ethanol), without median or marginal bands. AE row strongly procurved. PME greater than PLE and PME narrower than PLE row. Labium as long as wide or slightly longer than wide. Chelicerae with three promarginal teeth, the middle largest, and three retromarginal teeth of equal size. Male leg colouration uniform, females of some species with alternating light and dark pattern on legs. Leg lengths IV&gt; I&gt; II&gt; III. Legs I and II with scopulae on tarsus and metatarsus, also part of tibia in females. Legs III and IV with scopulae on tarsus and half of metatarsus, all of the metatarsus in females.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6409E01DFF95623AFCF110CBFCBCAFD0" blockId="7.[826,1442,1269,1811]" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">
<emphasis id="56C23C0FFF95623AFCF110CBFBB1AC43" box="[826,1141,1269,1290]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">
Natural history: 
<taxonomicName id="A3B69B9EFF95623AFBCA10CBFBB1AC43" authorityName="Roewer" authorityYear="1955" box="[1025,1141,1269,1290]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Hoggicosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hoggicosa</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
are predominately found through semi-arid and arid regions of 
<collectingCountry id="1CA1A08DFF95623AFAC8112DFAB6AC60" box="[1283,1394,1299,1321]" name="Australia" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">Australia</collectingCountry>
. All species build burrows and many construct doors from sand, with 
<taxonomicName id="A3B69B9EFF95623AFBCA116FFBA4AC2F" authorityName="Langlands &amp; Framenau" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Langlands &amp; Framenau" baseAuthorityYear="2010" box="[1025,1120,1361,1382]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Hoggicosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="snelli">
<emphasis id="56C23C0FFF95623AFBCA116FFBA4AC2F" box="[1025,1120,1361,1382]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">H. snelli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
using pebbles or debris as a door (
<bibRefCitation id="00279DECFF95623AFC581151FBE8ACCC" author="McKay RJ" box="[915,1068,1391,1413]" pageId="7" pageNumber="90" pagination="313 - 318" refId="ref23521" refString="McKay RJ. 1975. The wolf spiders of Australia (Araneae: Lycosidae): 5. Two new species of the bicolor group. Memoirs of the Queensland Museum 17: 313 - 318." type="journal article" year="1975">McKay, 1975</bibRefCitation>
). As the patch of macrosetae on the male cymbium is found only in adults, it is possible that these are used for courtship behaviour. We have made one observation of an attempted mating between a male and female of 
<taxonomicName id="A3B69B9EFF95623AFACE11D4FA89ACB6" authorityName="Langlands &amp; Framenau" authorityYear="2010" box="[1285,1357,1514,1535]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Hoggicosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alfi">
<emphasis id="56C23C0FFF95623AFACE11D4FA89ACB6" box="[1285,1357,1514,1535]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">H. alfi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. When approaching the female, the male used his palps to stroke the ground rapidly towards his body. This was carried out in repeated short bursts of less than a second, and created small ‘dugouts’ in the soft sand.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6409E01DFF95623AFC98129CFB3DAE5A" blockId="7.[826,1442,1269,1811]" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">
<taxonomicName id="A3B69B9EFF95623AFC98129CFC03AFFE" authorityName="Roewer" authorityYear="1955" box="[851,967,1698,1719]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Hoggicosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="56C23C0FFF95623AFC98129CFC03AFFE" box="[851,967,1698,1719]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">Hoggicosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are easily kept in the laboratory but can be difficult to rear past the penultimate stage. Our observations suggest that moulting can be triggered by hot and humid weather conditions.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6409E01DFF95623AFCF11367FB8DAE26" blockId="7.[826,1097,1881,1903]" box="[826,1097,1881,1903]" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">
<emphasis id="56C23C0FFF95623AFCF11367FC08AE27" box="[826,972,1881,1902]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">Distribution:</emphasis>
<collectingCountry id="1CA1A08DFF95623AFC1D1367FB81AE26" box="[982,1093,1881,1903]" name="Australia" pageId="7" pageNumber="90">Australia</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
